03585nam a22004935i 9780226207650DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017021801  a97802262076507 a10.7208/97802262076502doi  a(DE-B1597)550197  a(OCoLC)1004739887  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPQ7440.L29bI8813 2017 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aLalo, Eduardo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUselessness :bA Novel /cEduardo Lalo. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- t1. -- t2. -- t3. -- t4. -- t5. -- tSan Juan -- t1 -- t2 -- t30 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe streets of Paris at night are pathways coursing with light and shadow, channels along which identity may be formed and lost, where the grand inflow of history, art, language, and thought—and of love—can both inspire and enfeeble. For the narrator of Eduardo Lalo’s Uselessness, it is a world long desired. But as this young aspiring writer discovers upon leaving his home in San Juan to study—to live and be reborn—in the city of his dreams, Paris’s twinned influences can rip you apart. Lalo’s first novel, Uselessness is something of a bildungsroman of his own student days in Paris. But more than this, it is a literary précis of his oeuvre—of themes that obsess him still. Told in two parts, Uselessness first follows our narrator through his romantic and intellectual awakenings in Paris, where he elevates his adopted home over the moribund one he has left behind. But as he falls in and out of love he comes to realize that as a Puerto Rican, he will always be apart. Ending the greatest romance of his life—that with the city of Paris itself—he returns to San Juan. And in this new era of his life, he is forced to confront choices made, ambitions lost or unmet—to look upon lives not lived. A tale of the travails of youthful romance and adult acceptance, of foreignness and isolation both at home and abroad, and of the stultifying power of the desire to belong—and to be moved—Uselessness is here rendered into English by the masterful translator Suzanne Jill Levine. For anyone who has been touched by the disquieting passion of Paris, Uselessness is a stirring saga.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSpanish language materials. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aLevine, Suzanne Jill.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226207650423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226207650.jpg  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles